column2: Naval Models
Fire this decision to view information about your nation's ships in the mod.  At the moment only the majors' and Norway's ships are done.
This event will allow you to view your nation's naval models and what techs are required for each ship.

Graf Zeppelin-Class, Carrier IX

Launched on Dec. 8, 1938, the KMS Graf Zeppelin was the Kriegsmarine's first and only aircraft carrier.  The ship is a modification of the IJN Akagi, and was never completed.  It was the first of 6 carriers planned to be built as part of Build Plan III and the first of 4 as part of Plan Z.  A second carrier of this class was laid down but never launched, and was potentially to be named the Peter Strasser.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 6
Engine: 9
Deck Armor: 4
Destroyer MP Gun: 7

Europa-Class, Carrier X

The Europa was originally a merchant ship and was taken over by the Kriegsmarine in 1939 for use as a transport ship for Operation Sealion.  In 1942 plans were made to convert the transport to a carrier, but the design proved to have serious stability problems and was abandoned.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 7
Engine: 4
Deck Armor: 0
Destroyer MP Gun: 7

Flugzeugträger A-I-Class, Carrier XI

This carrier design was completed for the sole purpose of keeping the Kriegsmarine's naval architects from being sent to the Eastern Front.  Very few details exist about the background of this never-built ship, though the design itself survived the war.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 7
Engine: 9
Deck Armor: 4
Destroyer MP Gun: 7

Ausonia-Class, Light Carrier II

Launched on April 15, 1915 in Hamburg as an Italian passenger ship, Italy's entry in WW1 saw the ship be confiscated by Germany.  Plans were immediately drawn up to convert the incomplete ship to be an aircraft carrier due to be commissioned by 1918, but the course of the war did not allow the conversion to be completed.

Construction material: 1
Engine: 0
Cruiser Armor: 0
Destroyer MP Gun: 0

Kleiner Flugzeugträger-Class, Light Carrier IX

This ship came from a design study in 1937 to determine the usefullness of small carrier capable of fielding about 15 planes.  No ships were ordered and no construction started.

Construction material: 6
Cruiser Engine: 5
Cruiser Armor: 0
Destroyer MP Gun: 7

Seydlitz-Class, Light Carrier X

After the sinking of the Bismarck in 1941, the Hipper-class heavy cruiser Seydlidtz was chosen for conversion to an aircraft carrier as part of a larger program to expand Germany's naval aviation capacity.  The ship was renamed Weser and all construction halted in 1943.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 7
Cruiser Engine: 8
Cruiser Armor: 1
Destroyer MP Gun: 7

Jade-Class, Light Carrier XI

Germany's carrier conversion program of 1942, which saw work continue on the Graf Zeppelin and the conversion of the heavy cruiser Seydlitz, also saw the conversion of the merchant ships Jade, Scharnhorst, Gneisenau, Elbe, Weser, and Potsdam.  This class represents the 6 merchant ship conversions.  All construction work was halted in 1943.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 7
Engine: 2
Cruiser Armor: 0
Destroyer MP Gun: 7

De Grasse-Class, Light Carrier XII

Germany's carrier conversion program of 1942, which saw work continue on the Graf Zeppelin and the conversion of the heavy cruiser Seydlitz, also saw the conversion of 6 merchant ships and the captured French cruiser De Grasse.  All construction work was halted in 1943.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 7
Engine: 5
Cruiser Armor: 5
Destroyer MP Gun: 7

Deutschland-Class, Battleship I

Consisting of 5 ships, the Deutschland-class pre-dreadnought battleships served in both world wars.  After the Treaty of Versailles, Germany was allowed to retain the four surviving ships of the class, two of which remain in 1936.  The Schleswig-Holstein historically fired the first shots of WW2.

Destroyer MP Gun: 1
Main Guns: 0
Fast Battleship: No

Bayern-Class, Battleship II

First commissioned in 1916, the Bayern-class originally was supposed to be comprised of 4 ships, but only 2 were completed and both were scuttled at Scapa Flow.  These were the most modern of Imperial Germany's battleships and the last battleships completed prior to the Scharnhorst.

Techs needed:

Capital Armor: 4
Destroyer MP Gun: 1
Main Guns: 4
Fast Battleship: No

L 20-Class, Battleship III

The L 20 class was intended to replace the losses suffered at the Battle of Jutland.  This class was designed to be built quickly, and lacked anti-torpedo defense since adding such armor was a time-consuming process.  Due to the priority of the navy going to submarines, these ships were never completed.

Deutschland-Class (Modernized), Battleship VIII

This is a hypothetical class to cover the case of Germany deciding to reconstruct its aging pre-dreadnought battleships still in service.  Historically the Bismarck and Tirpitz replaced the two Deutschlands.

Construction material: 6

Bismarck-Class, Battleship IX

The Bismarck was launched on February 14, 1939 as a replacement for the battleship Hannover, with its sister ship Tirpitz being launched on April 1, 1939 as a replacement for the Schleswig-Holstein.  Both ships were intended to counter the new French battleships of the Dunkerque and Richeliu classes, but ended up performing convoy raiding duty.  The Bismarck was sunk by aircraft while at sea and the Tirpitz was sunk in port, having spent most of the war in Norway.

Construction material: 6
Engine: 8
Capital Armor: 3
Destroyer MP Gun: 7
Main Guns: 5
Fast Battleship: Yes

H 39-Class, Battleship X

The H-class was a series of designs intended to fullfill first Build Plan III and later Plan Z.  Both plans called for 6 H-class battleships to be built after the Bismarck, and construction of two H 39's began on July 15 and September 1 1939.  Both ships were scrapped and further battleship construction halted.

Derfflinger-Class, Battlecruiser I

The three Derfflinger-class battlecruisers were the the last of Germany's first-generation battlecruisers.  Ordered in response to the UK's Lion-class, two of the three ships were commissioned in time for the Battle of Jutland, where the Lützow was sunk.  The remaining two ships were scuttled at Scapa Flow.

Construction material: 0
Engine: 2
Capital Armor: 2
Destroyer MP Gun: 1
Main Guns: 1

Mackensen-Class, Battlecruiser II

Ordered before WW1, the four planned ships of this class were never finished, as resources were diverted to submarines.  These ships were a marked improvement over the earlier Derfflinger and formed the basis for the later Ersatz Yorck.

Destroyer MP Gun: 1

Ersatz Yorck-Class, Battlecruiser III

This class was to consist of 3 ships and were ordered in 1915 after the loss of the Armored Cruiser Yorck.  This class was the last battlecruiser design created by Imperial Germany, and was essentially a larger version of the Mackensen.

Construction material: 2
Engine: 3
Capital Armor: 1
Destroyer MP Gun: 1
Main Guns: 4

Scharnhorst-Class, Battlecruiser IX

The two ships of this class were ordered as replacements for the Deutschland-class Battleships Elsass and Hessen.  Both ships were originally slated to be Panzerschiff of the D-class, but were upgraded to capital ships after France announced the consctruction of the Dunkerque.  The Scharnhorst was launched on June 30. 1936 and commissioned on January 7, 1939 while the Gneisenau was launched on December 8, 1936 and commissioned on May 21, 1938.  Both ships were originally to have 11" main guns, but Hitler later ordered them to have 15" guns.  Since 15" main guns were not readily available, the 11" guns were used.  This model uses the 11" guns.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 6
Engine: 9
Capital Armor: 4
Destroyer MP Gun: 7
Main Guns: 2

Scharnhorst-Class (Upgunned), Battlecruiser X

The two ships of this class were ordered as replacements for the Deutschland-class Battleships Elsass and Hessen.  Both ships were originally slated to be Panzerschiffe of the D-class, but were upgraded to capital ships after France announced the consctruction of the Dunkerque.  The Scharnhorst was launched on June 30. 1936 and commissioned on January 7, 1939 while the Gneisenau was launched on December 8, 1936 and commissioned on May 21, 1938.  Both ships were originally to have 11" main guns, but Hitler later ordered them to have 15" guns.  Since 15" main guns were not readily available, the 11" guns were used historically.  This model uses the 15" guns.

KW 50-Class, Battlecruiser XI

The KW 50 was a private shipyard design from Kriegsmarinewerft Wilhelmshaven, created in the hope of securing a contract with the Kriegsmarine and to create an alternative to the O-class.  The design was incredibly fast, carried large main guns, but were poorly armored.

O-Class, Battlecruiser XII

The O-class battlecruiser was designed to meet Build Plan III's and Plan Z's requirements for 3 battlecruisers to be used for convoy raiding.  The O-class is a larger, better armed version of the P-class Panzerschiff.  The design made use of low-power longe-range diesel engines to extend the ships' operating range, large main guns, and weak armor barely able to withstand fire from heavy cruisers.  No ships of this class were built.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 8
Engine: 7
Capital Armor: 0
Destroyer MP Gun: 7
Main Guns: 5

Blücher-Class, Heavy Cruiser I

The SMS Blücher was Germany's last armored cruiser, intended to compete with the Royal Navy's new (at the time) battlecruisers.  The cruiser's role was to perform scouting duties for the main battle line, engage opposing reconnaissance ships, and participate in the main battle line once the major fighting began.  The Blücher was sunk during the Battle of Dogger Bank on January 24, 1915.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 0
Engine: 1
Cruiser Armor: 0
Destroyer MP Gun: 0
Main Guns: 6
Coastal Battleship: Yes

Deutschland-Class, Heavy Cruiser VII

The KMS Deutschland and its two sister ships were designed and funded by the Weimar Republic as replacements for the pre-dreadnought battleships Germany was allowed keep as per the terms of the Treaty of Versailles.  The three ships were classed as Panzerschiffe, or Armored Ships, meaning they were not legally heavy cruisers, which Germany was forbidden to build.  They were reclassed to be heavy cruisers by the Kriegsmarine in 1940.  By normal heavy cruiser standards the ships were heavily armored and armed, but slow.  Despite their heavy armor, in order to save weight the torpedo bulkheads and deck armor was thin or missing.

Engine: 6
Cruiser Armor: 2
Destroyer MP Gun: 7
Main Guns: 4
Coastal Battleship: No

D-Class, Heavy Cruiser VIII

Improved version of the Deutschland and authorized in 1933, two ships of this class were ordered as a counter to the French Dunkerque-class Battlecruiser.  One ship was laid down, but was canceled five months later to direct funds to the Scharnhorst, because the design was deemed too small to counter the French cruiser-killer.

Admiral Hipper-Class, Heavy Cruiser IX

The Anglo-German Naval Agreement, signed in 1935, permitted Germany to build a navy that was 35% of the size of the Royal Navy.  This meant that Germany could build five heavy cruisers that met the conditions of the London Naval Treaty, namely that tonnage was limited to 10,000 tons and main armament limited to 8" guns.  Historically, only 3 of the 5 were completed, with the Lützow being sold to the Soviet Union and an attempt was made to convert the nearly-completed Seydlitz to an aircraft carrier.

Main Guns: 5

P-Class, Heavy Cruiser X

The P-class Panzerschiffe were designed in 1937 to replace Germany's older cruisers, and the class was to number 12 ships.  By the time the war started, all 12 ships had been assigned shipyards, but all funding was canceled and diverted to other wartime needs.  No ships of this class were built.

Harald Haarfagre & Norge-Class, Heavy Cruiser I

This class of domestically-built coastal battleships consists of the ships Harald Haarfagre, Tordenskjold, and the Norge.  The first two ships were captured by Germany and used as flak batteries, while the Norge was sunk by German destroyers.

Björgvin-Class, Heavy Cruiser II

The two ships of this class were coastal battleships built by the UK on behalf of Norway prior to WW1.  After the outbreak of the war, the UK requisitioned both ships, paying 370,000 pounds to Norway as compensation.

Brummer-Class, Light Cruiser I

The SMS Brummer and its sister ship the Bremse were a pair of mine-laying cruisers for the Kaiserliche Marine.  These ships survived the war and due to their large operational range were often used to attack convoys and merchant traffic.  After WW1 ended they were scuttled at Scapa Flow.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 0
Engine: 2
Cruiser Armor: 1
Destroyer MP Gun: 1
Main Guns: 1

Königsberg-Class, Light Cruiser II

The Königsberg class consisted of four ships for the Kaiserliche Marine, all of which saw action in WW1.  The ships were an incremental improvement over the preceding Wiesbaden class and were used to escort minesweepers and to attack merchant shipping.  All four were scuttled at Scapa Flow.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 1
Engine: 2
Cruiser Armor: 1
Destroyer MP Gun: 1
Main Guns: 3

Emden-Class, Light Cruiser V

Constructed during the Weimar Republic, the Emden was the first large warship built by Germany after WW1.  Designed as a long-range commerce raider, the ship's design was hampered by British and French observers enforcing the terms of the Treaty of Versailles.  The Emden spent most of its career as a training ship and was sunk in Kiel by Allied bombers.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 4
Engine: 5
Cruiser Armor: 1
Destroyer MP Gun: 1
Main Guns: 3

K-Class, Light Cruiser VI

Built by the Weimar Republic, the 3 ships of the class were designed as commerce raiders.  However, the ships were welded together, which caused severe structural weakness during long journeys.  Combined with severe stability problems, the ships were confined to Germany's home waters.  Two of the ships were sunk during the invasion of Norway.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 4
Engine: 8
Cruiser Armor: 1
Destroyer MP Gun: 4
Main Guns: 4

Leipzig-Class, Light Cruiser VII

Built by the Weimar Republic, the 2 ships of the class were slight improvements over the earlier K-class.  Just like the ships of the K-class, the ships were welded together, which caused severe structural weakness during long journeys.  Combined with severe stability problems, the ships were confined to Germany's home waters.

Techs needed:
Construction material: 5
Engine: 5
Cruiser Armor: 1
Destroyer MP Gun: 5
Main Guns: 4

M-Class, Light Cruiser IX

Designed in 1936 as part of Hitler's naval rearmament program, the 12 ships of the M-class were to operate as scouts for Germany's convoy raiding squadrons.  Even during the design phase it became apparent that the ships' anti-air guns, main guns, and armor would be insufficient for their intended role, but alternative designs were no better.  The keels for two ships were laid down in 1938 and broken up after the start of WW2.

1936A-Class, Heavy Destroyer X

These heavy destroyers were unique in the Kriegsmarine in that they carried main guns typical of Germany's cruisers and were designed to operate away from Germany's coastline.  Germany's other destroyers were coastal defense ships, so these large destroyers are modeled as small cruisers.  In total 15 of these ships were built.

1938-Class, Heavy Destroyer XI

This destroyer was designed to operate alongside Germany's battleships as screens in the Atlantic and would've performed the traditional fleet role of a light cruiser.  No ships of this design were built, but 12 were ordered in 1939.  The design would evolve into the planned Spähkreuzer scouting cruiser prior to the start of WW2.

Momo-class-Class, Destroyer

This class of four medium destroyers was built during WW1 and acted as blue-water escorts to Japan's new Yamashiro and Ise battleships.  The ships were based at Malta and served as escorts for troop transports.  Two of the ships were retired and scrapped in 1940, one was used as a training hulk, and the fourth was sunk off of Okinawa in 1944.
